Advantages of JSON

Nested JSON allows for hierarchical organisation of data with nested levels of information. As each value can contain it’s own set of key-value pairs and as nesting is allowed, complex relationships and structures can be represented in a compact and standardised way.

An example is the reality of multiple genres and/or sub-genres. Each genre/sub-genre could be represented as a nested object under a key such as “genres” or “sub-genres”.

This implementation of nested JSON allows for flexible and structured representation of the genres. This allows for easier analysis of songs based on their genres and sub-genres.

Key features of my playlist

  1. The graph which shows the percentage of songs which are explicit in the playlist grouped by a song’s primary genre.
  2. An annotation underneath the graph which gives the percentage of the largest percentage on the graph.
  3. The mean price of a given song in a given currency.
  4. How many seconds in the longest song of the playlist.

SQL Examples 

SELECT trackViewUrl AS track_url,
       trackPrice AS price,
       durationMillisecond / 1000 AS duration_seconds,
       primaryGenreName AS primary_genre,
       trackExplicitness AS explicitness,
       LENGTH(trackName) AS track_name_length,
       trackName AS track,
       LENGTH(artistName) AS artist_name_length,
       artistName AS artist
FROM tbl_songs
WHERE price <= 2.00
LIMIT 20;

Two Examples of SQL

“SELECT” allows for customising the specific variables we wish to have in our table. “LIMIT” allows for limiting the amount of objects in the table.

Appendix 

library(tidyverse)
library(jsonlite)
library(dplyr)
library(magick)

query_1 <- "https://itunes.apple.com/search?term=stealing+things&limit=200"
response_example <- fromJSON(query_1)

# Cheap songs about criminals with no explicit language
# Aim is a playlist of affordable songs to be used while committing crimes with your whole family
# Affordable in this case means 2 dollars USD or less
query_actual <- "https://itunes.apple.com/search?term=criminal&limit=200"
response <- fromJSON(query_actual)
initial_playlist <- response$results

# Query is "criminal". Affordable songs for committing crime
# Make highly customised playlist catering to our aims
my_playlist <- initial_playlist %>%
  filter(str_detect(kind, "song")) %>%
  mutate(artistNameLength = nchar(artistName), 
         trackNameLength = nchar(trackName), 
         durationSeconds = trackTimeMillis / 1000) %>%
  select(artistName,
         artistNameLength,
         trackName, 
         trackNameLength,
         trackExplicitness, 
         primaryGenreName,
         trackPrice,
         durationSeconds,
         trackViewUrl,
         currency) %>%
  rename(artist = 1,
         artist_name_length = 2,
         track = 3,
         track_name_length = 4,
         explicitness = 5,
         primary_genre = 6,
         price= 7,
         duration_seconds = 8,
         track_url = 9) %>%
  slice(1:20)

# my_playlist %>%
#  print()

# Write my_playlist as an CSV 
write_csv(my_playlist, "my_playlist.csv")

# Group by a variable and summarise.
# Gets the percentage of songs which are explicit for each primary genre
percentage_data <- my_playlist %>%
  group_by(primary_genre) %>%
  summarise(percentage_explicit_songs = round(sum(explicitness == "explicit") / n(), 2) * 100)

# Using knowledge from previous assignments to make a bar graph
percentage_data_graph <- ggplot (data = percentage_data) +
  geom_col(aes(x = primary_genre, y = percentage_explicit_songs, fill = primary_genre)) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 100))+
  labs(title = "Percentage of explicit criminal songs by genre?",subtitle = "Comparing the percentage of explicit songs about criminals in each primary genre", x = "Primary genre", y = "Percentage of songs which are explicit")

ggsave("percentage_data_graph.png", percentage_data_graph, height = 6, width = 9, dpi = 320)

# Create an annotated image
graph_image <- image_read("percentage_data_graph.png")

maximum_percentage <- percentage_data$percentage_explicit_songs %>%
  max()
  
annotation_text <- paste("The highest percentage of explicit songs about criminals grouped by primary genre is", maximum_percentage, "%.")
annotation_text_image <- image_blank(color = "pink", height = 200, width = (9 * 320)) %>%
  image_annotate(annotation_text, size = 50, gravity = "center")
annotation_text_image %>%
  image_write("annotation.png")

annotation_image_vector <- c(graph_image, annotation_text_image)

annotated_graph_image <- image_append(annotation_image_vector, stack = TRUE)
annotated_graph_image %>%
  image_write("annotated_percentage_data_graph.png")
